rall: good decision, calm, technical, but communication, ego, lack of development.\n\nCandidate D:\n- responds to unexpected events adequately (positive)\n- can concentrate very well (positive)\n- solves problems extremely well (positive)\n- takes responsibility seriously (positive)\n- regarded as a know-it-all (negative)\n- has a hot temper (negative)\n\nOverall: strong problem solving, responsibility, concentration, but attitude issues (know-it-all, hot temper) could affect crew cooperation.\n\nWe need to pick best for long-distance pilot: reliability, decision under pressure, teamwork, communication, technical competence, long-term suitability.\n\nAssess each:\n\nA: strong anticipation, spatial vision, leadership, but show-off and not open to new ideas may hinder teamwork and adaptability. Leadership good but could be overbearing.\n\nB: conscientious, stress handling, weather assessment, computer skills important for long flights. Weak number memory could be critical for calculations; nasty remarks harmful to crew.\n\nC: quick correct decisions, calm, tech understanding good. Communication difficulty and egocentric, unwilling to further education problematic for long-term development.\n\nD: problem solving, concentration, responsibility, good for unexpected events. But hot temper and know-it-all could cause crew friction, especially on long flights.\n\nWhich is best? We weigh positives vs negatives. B's interpersonal issue is nasty remarks, which is severe for crew cooperation. Also weak number memory is a safety risk. C's communication difficulty is also severe. D's hot temper could be dangerous under stress. A's show-off and not open to new ideas may affect teamwork but perhaps less severe than outright nasty remarks or hot temper. A's technical strengths are high.\n\nThus A might be the best despite attitude concerns. However, not open to new ideas could affect adaptability to new procedures, which is important for long-distance flights. Show-off may affect crew morale.\n\nWe need to consider which candidate has the least severe negatives relative to positives. B's nasty remarks is a strong negative. C's communication difficulty and egocentric also strong. D's hot temper also strong. A's negatives are more about attitude but not directly harmful? Show-off could be mitigated; not open to new ideas could be a problem but maybe less than hot temper.\n\nThus provisional preference: Candidate A.\n\nConfidence moderate, maybe 65%.\n\nWe should note uncertainties: we don't know actual impact of show-off, not open to new ideas, or how severe B's memory issue is, etc. Ask other agents for any additional info on teamwork or crew feedback for each candidate.\n\nBut we need to produce public message summarizing.\n\nProceed."}
